Git Tutorial

Git: The Information Manager from Hell

Alberto Hernandez-Melian

Introduction

  • Git is a version control system (VCS) created in 2005.

  • Originally used to help development of the Linux Kernel.

  • Now by far most popular way of tracking code changes.

Some definitions

A repository is organised as a graph of commits.

Repository

A collection of all previous versions of your project.

Commit

A single snapshot of your project.

Let there be light!

We create a repository by calling git init in our project folder.

Hey, hey, what's going on? ♫♫

Use git status to get information about the current state.

Baby's first function

Use git add to tell git which changes to include. 

def add2(x,y):
  return x + y

Voilà, first commit!

We create a new check-point by using git commit.

Why two steps?

We might not want to record all changes at the same time:

Worktree

Your actual code in the file-system.

Index

Changes to be included in next commit (staged).

Repository

Where all previous commits are stored.

What did we just do?

Use git show to get information about a commit.

And thy hash shall be...

A commit hash uniquely identifies a version of the code:

  • A hash is a short string which fingerprints a longer one.

  • Git works by hashing together source code and previous commits.

  • The hash also includes the current time and other information.

Spotting the difference

We can make more edits and see what's changed using git diff.

For the most annoying branches

No man is an island

Git is designed to allow collaboration between many people.

git remote

Tell git where to find other repositories.

git pull

Apply changes from others to local repository1.

git push

Share local changes with another repository.

1

Always before git push (and consider --rebase)

Good Cop, Bad Cop

git bisect

Find commit which introduced a bug.

git blame

Find who committed a particular line.

git grep

Find a pattern in past versions of code.

Many more useful commands...

git restore

To get an old version of a file.

git revert

Make a commit to undo a previous one.

git cherry-pick

Copy a single commit to another branch.

git rebase

Rewrite history 1.

1

A great and terrible power, but sometime useful.
